134. **Clever Twist:** The garden is a *memory of the dead*—and every flower is a soul;  
135. **Clever Worldbuilding Feature:** The city’s rain is made of *unspoken words*—and every drop holds a secret;  
136. **Scene:** Rook kneels in the mud—*the flower blooms, and the wind carries a name*.

137. **Protagonist:** A clockmaker named Elara, who fixes timepieces that run backward;  
138. **Dilemma:** She finds a clock that runs backward—*and it’s her own*;  
139. **Decision:** She must either fix it or let it keep running;  
140. **Climax:** She winds it—*and the city begins to unlive*;  
141. **Outcome:** She realizes she’s not fixing time—*she’s undoing her own life*;  
142. **Clever Twist:** The clocks don’t run backward—they *remember*;  
143. **Clever Worldbuilding Feature:** In this city, time is not linear—it’s *circular*, and every moment is a loop;  
144. **Scene:** Elara stands in the street—*the clock ticks, and the world begins to repeat*.

